<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>velutinus</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>patula</i>, <i>Arctostaphylos</i> <i>viscida</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>tridentata</i> ssp. <i>vaseyana</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>cordulatus</i>, <i>Ceanothus</i> <i>cuneatus</i>, <i>Chrysolepis</i> <i>sempervirens</i>, <i>Holodiscus</i> <i>discolor</i>, <i>Prunus</i> <i>emarginata</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>sadleriana</i>, <i>Quercus</i> <i>vacciniifolia</i> and <i>Symphoricarpos</i> <i>mollis</i>. Emergent conifer trees may be present at low cover. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 4 m; canopy is intermittent to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Ceanothus velutinus</i> > 50% relative cover in the shrub canopy (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b).</li>
		
		<li><i>Ceanothus velutinus</i> is >30% relative cover in the shrub layer (Boul et al. 2021b).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Ridges, shallow draws, and upper slopes.  </div>
</div>

        
