<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceanothus velutinus </i>is a large, spreading, many-stemmed shrub that grows to 6 m tall. The roots harbor nitrogen-fixing actinomycetes. Plants produce seeds abundantly; these are propelled a short distance when capsules open explosively. Ants, birds, and rodents disperse the seeds, which accumulate in duff and soil as a seed bank. Germination requires cold and heat stratification (Anderson 2001b, Francis 2002a). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Ceanothus velutinus </i>grows throughout much of the West, where it is associated with many forest types from South Dakota to the Pacific coast. Stands develop along mountain slopes after disturbances, such as fire or logging. The two varieties, the inland var. <i>velutinus </i>and the taller, coastal var. <i>hookeri, </i>have similar ecologies (Fross and Wilken 2006), so we include both in the alliance. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
