    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        
            <p>The range of <i>Ceanothus velutinus</i> includes the Northern California Coast (263A) and Northern California Coast Ranges (M261B).</p>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Aa-b, Ad-g, Aj, Al, An, Ap). Stands exist throughout the section at montane elevations, as in old clearcuts in Adorni and Upper Goose Creek RNAs (Cheng 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Modoc Plateau</b> (M261Gb-d, Gf, Gi-n). Stands are widespread in higher mountains surrounded by Abies concolor, Pinus jeffreyi, and other coniferous forests. Some isolated stands occur on mesic slopes on Clear Lake Hills surrounded by <i>Artemisia tridentata</i> and other Great Basin shrublands.</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dd-f, Dh, Dj, Dl). Stands with similar species composition to those in Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b) mix with those of <i>Artemisia tridentata</i> and other Great Basin shrub types at elevations between 1900 and 2500 m in the Bodie area.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Bd). No description available</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Ea-d, Ej-l, En, Er, Et). Stands at Babbitt Peak RNA (Cheng 2004) and Yosemite National Park (Keeler-Wolf et al. 2003b) are almost completely limited to the eastern slope.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern Cascades</b> (M261Da, Dc-d, Df-j, Dm). Stands at Antelope Creek Lakes, Mud Lake, and Shasta Mudflow RNAs (Cheng 2004) offer several facets of the alliance.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Ceanothus velutinus </i>stands occupy recently burned or logged areas. Site quality appears important in determining the rate at which conifers replace the shrubs. Shrub fields can persist over thin soil, and individual plants are not shaded out in open woodlands. On productive, managed sites, shrubs compete with plantation conifers and slow tree growth (Anderson 2001b, Francis 2002a). Managers use herbicides and manual release techniques to increase conifer growth. Frequent fires can deplete seed banks of <i>C. velutinus</i>. </div>
</div>

    

    

